  "summary": "Frances DeWinter visits Bobby at a sanatorium, bringing lilies. Bobby explains that he has become a sensation at the facility after surviving an overdose of eight morphine tablets. He reveals that the morphine was placed in a beer bottle, noting that the paper on the bottle's cap had not been sticking properly, which suggests someone spiked the drink while he was asleep. An analysis of the leftover beer confirmed it contained lethal amounts of the drug, though no source for the morphine was found at the bar.\n\nFrankie proposes a theory connecting Bobby’s poisoning to the previous incident where a man named Prichard was pushed off a cliff. She argues that Bobby was not targeted for an inheritance or revenge, but because the perpetrator believed Bobby witnessed the crime. Frankie suggests that even if Bobby did not see the actual push, he might have noticed a distinguishing physical feature of the killer. She further links this to the strange job offer Bobby received from a foreign company, theorizing that the perpetrators first tried to move him overseas before attempting to kill him. Bobby remains skeptical of the connection, noting that another person, Thomas, was present at the cliff but was not poisoned. Despite his doubts, Bobby admits the theory makes him feel important. Frankie concludes the visit by promising to return the following day.",
